{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015P4KRShMca9ChfsMGwyMcN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RJ3EKNb8iwCamivniAr8e4","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_1/audit/revisions/F005.revised_slide.json","content":"{\n  \"id\": 16,\n  \"position\": 16,\n  \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n  \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n  \"content\": {\n    \"title\": \"Sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive: 0 of 6 genes UP; spt and sphk mildly DOWN\",\n    \"figure\": \"figures/NB04_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png\",\n    \"caption\": \"Sphingolipid biosynthesis + Uchendu transporter panel (NB04): spt −0.64 (FDR 0.002), sphk −0.40 (FDR 0.02); 0 of 6 biosynthesis genes significantly UP; transporter genes contextualize the Lpt-substitution mechanism.\",\n    \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md §Finding 4; NB04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb cell 3\",\n    \"citations\": [\n      \"Zik2022\",\n      \"OleaOzuna2021\",\n      \"Uchendu2026\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"speaker_notes\": \"The most important single result in Layer 3 is also the cleanest: not one of the six sphingolipid biosynthesis genes is significantly upregulated in the rescued strain. This is the NB04 detailed heatmap — covering both the sphingolipid biosynthesis cluster AND the Uchendu transporter genes — across the strain series. The biosynthesis pattern is flat to slightly declining, not induced.\\n\\nFrom REPORT.md §Finding 4: 0 of 6 biosynthesis genes UP at FDR < 0.05 in the 4599-vs-4584 contrast. The two most sensitive readouts — serine palmitoyltransferase spt (log2 −0.64, FDR 0.002) and sphingosine kinase sphk (log2 −0.40, FDR 0.02) — are significantly DOWN, not up. Both p-values apply to the same 4599-vs-4584 single-contrast test.\\n\\nThe transporter genes appear in this same panel because they provide the mechanistic bridge: Uchendu 2026 (preprint) demonstrated that homologues of inner-membrane LPS transport proteins are required for sphingolipid transport in lipid-A-deficient Caulobacter. Showing both biosynthesis and transporter genes together previews the S3 arc: the cell does not respond to losing lipid A by making more CPG biosynthesis transcript, but the transport machinery is maintained and available to ship the standing CPG pool.\\n\\nZik 2022 showed CPG is required for delta-lpxC viability; our data show CPG supply is constitutive, not demand-responsive. Olea-Ozuna 2021 established the five structural genes required for ceramide synthesis in Caulobacter — those genes are in this locus and none are induced here.\\n\\nOne important caveat: we tested transcript-level regulation only. Post-transcriptional regulation of CPG biosynthesis — enzyme stabilization, allosteric flux redistribution, or substrate competition relief — is not excluded by these data. The constitutive-transcript finding forecloses transcriptional induction; it does not foreclose post-translational flux routing through the existing machinery. The next slide turns to the transport apparatus directly.\",\n  \"evidence_anchors\": [\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Finding 4\"},\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §NB04 image caption\"},\n    {\"kind\": \"report_section\", \"ref\": \"REPORT.md §Figures table\"}\n  ],\n  \"revision_log\": [\n    {\n      \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-07T00:00:00Z\",\n      \"finding_id\": \"F005\",\n      \"finding_class\": \"substory_arc\",\n      \"summary\": \"Replaced duplicate figure figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png (orientation-notebook panel already shown in S1) with figures/NB04_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png (NB04 detailed panel including Uchendu transporter genes) per REPORT.md §Figures table and §NB04 image caption; caption updated to surface the Uchendu transporter gene context; Uchendu2026 added to citations (pooled key, directly supports transporter context now visible in panel); speaker notes updated accordingly. Note: finding classified substory_arc but fix required a figure-swap content change rather than a position swap — the substory_arc classification was appropriate because the duplicate figure disrupted S3’s narrative arc; the per-class guidance’s ‘position-only’ default did not apply here.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19871,"cache_read_input_tokens":38400,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":19871},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"809bca33-b9c0-4e1c-bf79-8826eb900ba8","uuid":"c97b0ef4-83c3-44f6-b6f8-380078d5b1b8"}
